@node "FAQSAutoRepeat" "There are many missing or auto repeating keys!"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "There are many missing or auto repeating keys"}

You should check the shielding of your interface!@{par}

Under normal circumstances the shield wires should be only connected on one side. Well, in this
case you can ignore this rule, because the MMKeyboard interface acts between keyboard and amiga. The
keyboard shield is already disconnected on one side of the keyboard cable, so you should connect the
shields on your interface.@{par}

A metalized box containing your interface may be good additional shield! @{b}Make sure your hardware
isn't in contact with the box, because the box acts like metal and connects everything as good as it
shields.@{ub}@{par}

If the problem is still present, then the wire may be to long. Under normal circumstances this
isn't a real problem, but it may cause trouble. I suggest to use a small wire (10cm) on each side of
the interface. Later you can try an extender cable.@{par}

If you build your interface into a tower or desktop system make sure not to use to long wire for LED
connection. It may be required to use a line driver to avoid PIC trouble.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSTrouble" "The keyboard is making trouble!"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "The keyboard is making trouble!"}

The data part of the PIC is holding the PIC configuration! The software you used to program the PIC
didn't program the default values. So the previous state (aka trash) of the data memory is
interpreted by MMKeyboard as config.@{par}

Now there are three possibilities why this happens:@{par}

1. If the keyboard is working, then use the @{"PIC set-up window" link "PICC"} to create a valid
configuration. Make sure you enter a proper password, too!@{par}

2. If the scroll lock light is flashing and the keyboard is not working (if MMKeyboard commodity is
running, the mouse isn't working, too!) then the only way is to use the MMKeyboardNP.hex. This file
isn't asking for a password and you're able to @{"disable" link "PICC"} or set-up it. After doing
this, reprogram the PIC by using the normal MMKeyboard.hex. This problem isn't caused by MMKeyboard.
Your PIC programming tool didn't wrote the data part of the PIC, where the (default) settings are
stored.@{par}

3. If the scroll lock light is flashing after pressing the reset combination, then the system keyboard
interrupt was killed some how. This may happen by games without any keyboard support. This is normal
and even happens when using an original Amiga keyboard. The Amiga isn't responding to the reset
warning and the keyboard or in this case MMKeyboard is delaying the reset. Just wait a few seconds
and your system will restart.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSHardNW" "My hardware isn't working! Why?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "My hardware isn't working! Why?"}

Well, that is not that easy! You should not use a wireless keyboard for testing, because that may
cause additional problems. The best thing is to use a cheap standard Windows keyboard.@{par}

First remove the PIC and connect pin 2 and pin 6 on the PIC socket. Do the same with pin 3 and pin
7! The result is a very short keyboard extender!@{par}

Now check all wires from the keyboard side to the amiga side! The 4 wires
(5V, GND, Clock, Data) must be 1:1 connected.@{par}

If everything is ok, then use your hardware (don't remove the bridges) to connect an
@{b}Amiga-keyboard@{ub} to your Amiga. If no Amiga-keyboard is available use a PC-keyboard and a PC
insteat! (remember: The hardware acts like an extender cable)@{par}

Some things you should check until the extender is working:@{par}

Is there keyboard power? (keyboard lights are flashing on power up?)@{par}
Is GND connected to the PIC (Pin 5)?@{par}
Is MCLR (Pin 4) connected to 5V?@{par}
Are the values for the resistor and the capacity correct?@{par}
Are resistor and capacity connected correct? (Pin 16, 5V, GND)@{par}
Are clock and data are connected to the right PIC pins?@{par}
Are clock and data swapped on one or both sides of the PIC?@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSNoPassword" "After a system crash I don't get a password requester! Why?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "After a system crash I don't get a password requester! Why?"}

The reason is simple!@{par}

How should the keyboard (MMKeyboard hardware) notice that a crash happens? The same is happening you use a
reset tool to restart your system.@{par}

If you want to secure your system then use the @{"password key (ScrLock)" link "PICCPaHo"}!
Once used it's impossible to reset the system by keyboard and any system crash or software reset
is only reloading the system and asking for a password again. Without password the system is totally
locked!@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSHardBuy" "Is there a way to buy the hardware?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Is there a way to buy the hardware?"}

Yes! You should contact me via @{"EMail" link "Author"} first.@{par}

I am only assembling a small number of interfaces at once, so it may take a while before you'll get one.@{par}

@{"Here" link "/Pictures/MMK_Mersmann1.jpg/main"} you can see what you'll get. Of course there'll be
a @{"PIC" link "FAQSPIC"} equipped, when you'll get it, but anyone knows what an IC is and the
interesting part is the interface. Here is the same @{"interface closed" link "/Pictures/MMK_Mersmann2.jpg/main"}.
The interface connectors are PS/2 only! If you need a DIN connector then you can get a interface for
1 Euro or by a interface in your locale computer store.@{par}

You have to pay 25 Euro (50 DM) for each interface. This is only for parts, shipping and the time I
spent to build them. For selling into non Europe country's it's required to pay 30 Euro.@{par}

Don't ask for programmed PIC chips. I made bad experiences, so I only sent complete interfaces.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSHardHard" "Can I use MMKeyboard with my A1200 Tower?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Can I use MMKeyboard with my A1200 Tower?"}

Yes and No! When your tower is using a standard A2000, A3000 or A4000 keyboard then you can use
MMKeyboard without any problem. If there is a PC keyboard connected then there is no chance to
connect MMKeyboard there!

It's not possible to plug the MMKeyboard interface into your old interface, but you can
connect the interface @{"to your mainboard" link "/Pictures/A1200Connector.ilbm/Main"}.@{par}

This is because your old interface expects a PC keyboard to be plugged in. The MMKeyboard hardware is acting like an
Amiga keyboard. It's not possible to link keyboard interfaces together.@{par}


@endnode
@node "FAQSPIC" "What is a PIC?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What is a PIC?"}

A PIC is a one chip computer! It contains a processor, RAM, program (FLASH) and data (EEPROM)
memory!@{par}

Most of it's pins can be used free by the internal program. It's possible to read and write any IO
state the application requires.@{par}

A PIC can be used as clock, as combination lock, as copy protection for software and much more!
Years ago big circuits or expensive chips were required to do what a little PIC is doing alone.@{par}

There are many PIC types available. The most used processors are the PIC16c84 and the PIC16f84
created by Microchip. The only difference is more memory and EEPROM data space. The c84
isn't available anymore, because the f84 is better and compatible.@{par}

Before a PIC can used in a circuit, its required to set-up the program and the data. This
procedure requires a special device: A PIC programmer.@{par}

When programming a PIC it's required to keep an eye on the fuses. There are fuses for enabling the
WatchDog-Timer (WDT), the PowerUp-Timer (PWRT) and the CodeProtection (CP). The WDT must not be used
without program support, because nothing is working in the result. The PWRT takes care of the
PowerUp and delays a little to allow the hardware to settle. This fuse should be enabled, as long as
there isn't reason for immediate start-up of the PIC. The CP Fuse disables the PIC readout. It's not
possible to readout the PIC any more.

@endnode
@node "FAQSPICSetup" "How to change the PIC configuration?"

@{MS "How to change the PIC configuration?"}

Before making changes to the PIC set-up you need your personal settings!@{par}

Use the @{"PIC set-up window" link "PICC"} to enable the features you need. The configuration is done
by the @{"set-up PIC configuration" link "PICCConf"} gadget in the same window.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSPICStupidSetup" "Why is the PIC configuration so stupid?"

@{MS "Why is the PIC configuration so stupid?"}

That's a very good question!@{par}

If the PIC configuration should be changed without an external programmer, then it is required that
the PIC is doing the flash writing. The problem is that the PIC is unaware of the users wishes, so
the user needs to enter the set-up by hand. The lucky part is that the keyboard is already
connected.@{par}

In theory it's possible to program the PIC by using MMKeyboardPrefs on Amiga, but this would
require an additional protocol to transmit chars in the opposite direction. The problem is that
the PIC code memory is to small to hold this additional transfer stuff. On the other side the Amiga
part would be a bad hack, which would require a system disable during transfer.@{par}

I think this "set-up for stupids" is a good alternative.@{par}

I you don't want to use the GUI feel free to use an editor or the shell. Press
"LAmiga" + "RAmiga" + "F12" to turn the PIC into set-up mode. The PIC is
printing a "+" to indicate that this is the main menu. Now press "1" for
password, "2" for configuration or any other number or char to leave the menu
and return to normal keyboard operation.@{par}

After pressing "1" you must enter the password. Press the "return"-key (not the
"enter"-key) to finalise the password and return to the main menu ("+").@{par}

After selecting "2" you must enter the @{"configuration value" link "PICCValu"}.
After pressing the last value the PIC returns into the main menu ("+").@{par}

This is an example to set the password to "password" and the @{"configuration value" link "PICCValu"}
to "f2c5ff3f". The "+" chars are created by the PIC,
when it re-enters the main menu. On the screen it looks like this:@{par}

+1password@{par}
+2f2c5ff3f+3@{par}

After the "+" character the menu selection ("1","2" or "3") and the argument is following.@{par}

@{b}A special note to any advanced amiga user! Using the clipboard or any other key inserting tool
isn't working, because the settings must be typed in by keyboard only!@{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSTune" "Is there a way to tune the hardware?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Is there a way to tune the hardware?"}

Yes! You are able to connect 4 LEDs to display the keyboard status of "NumLock", "CapsLock" and
"ScrollLock". This is very useful when using a keyboard without these LEDs (e.g. Logitech
ITouch).@{par}

The "ScrollLock" light isn't required on Amiga, but I Used it to indicate password request and "Wait
for 10 seconds time-out" mode when using a reset handler.@{par}

The last line is active if the password is correct! This line is also useful if you want to disable
other hardware until the password is correct (Mouse, ...)! Just let me know what you used the line
for! It's possible to connect the password line direct with pin 6 of the mouse connector. This
disables the mouse until the password is correct. This is also working when using the PS2M
interface.@{par}

A special feature is hidden behind the PowerUp Line. Just think about activating your Amiga by
keystroke. When using an @{"ATX power supply" link "FAQSATX"} @{"this can be done" link "FAQSPICPowerSW"} without
any additional hardware.@{par}

It's also possible to switch power on or of by using a switch on your computer case.
A special PIC line is used to handle this.@{par}

Take a look on this @{"picture" link "/Pictures/Optional.ilbm/MAIN"} for more information.

@endnode
@node "FAQSATX" "I want to adapt an ATX power supply, but I don't know how!"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "I want to adapt an ATX power supply, but I don't know how!"}

@{b}Any modifications are on your risk only. I am not responsible for any hard or software damage.@{ub}@{par}

The easiest way is to use an ATX extender.  Cut it into two peaces. Cut the power connector of your
old power supply. Connect Amiga plug and the ATX connector by using the correct voltages. Make sure
that all connections are correct, or you blow up all your hardware at once. Isolate unused
voltages as wall as the connections. The result is a ATX to Amiga interface.@{par}

Now there are only PowerGood, Standby GND, Standby 5V and Standby Switch left.@{par}

PowerGood must be connected to the main board, if the board supports PowerGood. The A4000D is the
only Amiga supporting this line. The A4000T isn't supporting PowerGood. Just connect it or isolate
it.@{par}

Now there are only Standby GND, Standby 5V and Standby Switch left. This lines needed to be
connected like shown in this @{"picture" link "/Pictures/ATXSupport.ilbm/MAIN"}.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSPICPowerSW" "How can I switch my Amiga on and off by using the keyboard?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "How can I switch my Amiga on and off by using the keyboard?"}

Very easy! You need to connect a standard @{"ATX power supply" link "FAQSATX"} and build the
standard @{"MMKeyboard hardware" link "/Pictures/Hardware.ilbm/MAIN"}.@{par}

There are only three things to take care of:@{par}

The PIC and Keyboard power must be connected to 5V Standby of the @{"ATX power supply" link "FAQSATX"}. Important
is that there @{b}must not@{ub} be any other 5V connected.@{par}

Connect all GND lines on the interface. It may work, but to guarantee a stable hardware the
connections are recommended. The lines to connect are: Standby-GND (power supply) GND (original
Keyboard connector (not available on A1200)) and the GND line of the new PS/2 keyboard connector.@{par}

The Standby-Switch wire needs to be connected to PIC (Pin 11).@{par}

Here a small @{"picture" link "/Pictures/ATXSupport.ilbm/MAIN"} to show the needed connections.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSCOMM" "Do I need the commodity? It seems to work without!"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Do I need the commodity? It seems to work without!"}

Of course the hardware is working without the commodiy! The commodity is only required for multimedia key
support.

@endnode
@node "FAQSMMKS" "Is it possible to use the additional keys with other software?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Is it possible to use the additional keys with other software?"}

Yes and No! Multimedia keys like Play, Stop or EMail are not working!@{par}

Key like  "Insert", "HOME", "END", "PAGE_UP", "PAGE_DOWN", F11, F12 are theoretically working with all
programs. Practically is the keyboard device filtering "HOME" and "END".@{par}

When using the Amithlon-Version all keys are used by the standard
@{"rawkey-map" link "FAQSRAW"}. (expect HOME and END). I got this special standard description
to late and decided to skip the standard to stay compatible with sold hardware.
If you want to use the standard then this is possible by using the macro
@{"IEvent" link "MacrosIEvent"}.@{par}

@{"Here" link "FAQSRAW"} is a table of all standard raw keys.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSGAME" "Can I play my old games with your hardware?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Can I play my old games with your hardware?"}

Of course! There shouldn't be any problem!

@endnode
@node "FAQSNewSoftOldHard" "Can I use my old hardware with your commodity?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Can I use my old hardware with your commodity?"}

No! Standard keyboard interfaces are transmitting the amiga keys only, so there is nothing for the
commodity to do.@{par}

If you own a self made hardware, then make sure it's the same hardware. In this case just reprogram
the PIC and you're able to use all new features.@{par}

My hardware is using a special transmission technique that allows my commodity to filter all non
amiga keys out. This is very tricky, because the keyboard transmission must be 100% compatible when
working without the commodity. This is required to support games or old applications which are
handling the keyboard stuff itself.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSAmithlon" "What is Amithlon?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What is Amithlon?"}

Amithlon is a kernel that allows to run AmigaOS on standard pc hardware.@{par}

This may sound like a simple amiga emulator, but it isn't. The 68K commands are recompiled into x86
command in time. (JIT compiler). The audio, video and other IO hardware isn't implemented at all.
New devices and drivers allow to use normal PC stuff with maximum speed.@{par}

The user it self is unaware of Amithlon, because it looks like a "Super-Amiga" and not like a
emulator on a pc. A normal PC (P3-866Mhz) used with Amithlon has the speed of an Amiga with 68040 with more than
1Ghz. Due the fact that PC graphic boards are supported, there isn't a slow down even when using a 1280
* 1024 Workbench screen with the maximum amount colors (32 Bit).@{par}

More information on Amithlon can be found at: www.amithlon.de, www.amithlon.net and www.vmc.de@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSAmithlonXL" "What is AmithlonXL?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What is AmithlonXL?"}

AmithlonXL is an updated version of @{"Amithlon" link "FAQSAmithlon"} made by
Harald Frank. It has new amiga side drivers including a new input.device.@{par}

More information on Amithlon can be found at: www.amithlon.de, www.amithlon.net and www.vmc.de@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSMMKAmithlon" "Can I use MMKeyboard with Amithlon?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Can I use MMKeyboard with Amithlon?"}

Yes and No! The hardware is only working with Amiga systems and not with PC hardware, because there is no
interface needed to connect a PC keyboard to a pc.@{par}

The special version of MMKeyboard is working on Amithlon. It's a little tricky to get
the key stuff from the emulation side to the Amiga side, but it seem to work without any trouble.@{par}

There are a few "restrictions". Sounds bad, but it's logic:@{par}

The hardware password isn't available, because we don't have any MMKeyboard hardware.@{par}

The @{"reset handler" link "FAQSResetHandler"} isn't working, because the current Amithlon version don't not support the system reset handler.
If this changes, then MMKeyboard will support the reset handler automatically.@{par}

The keys PRT-SCR, SCROLL and PAUSE aren't available, because they are handled different and can't be patched.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSMMKOSXL" "Is it possible to use MMKeyboard with UAE or with AmigaOS XL?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Is it possible to use MMKeyboard with UAE or with AmigaOS XL?"}

NO! UAE and the QNX version are normal Amiga emulations. MMKeyboard requires the Amithlon-kernel,
because it needs some functions, that are not available with these versions.@{par}

Amithlon is the first choice to get a real Amiga feeling on x86 hardware.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSMorphOS" "What is MorphOS?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What is MorphOS?"}

MorphOS is an Amiga compatible OS for Pegasos PPC hardware. There is also a
version for 68K Amigas planned.

MorphOS combines the advantages of modern hardware and AmigaOS.

@endnode
@node "FAQSMMKMorphOS" "Can I use MMKeyboard with MorphOS?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Can I use MMKeyboard with MorphOS?"}

Yes! The hardware is only working with Amiga systems and not with PC hardware, because there is no
interface needed to connect a PC keyboard to a pc.@{par}

There is a special version of MMKeyboard which works on MorphOS. You'll need
MorphOS 1.5 for full operation. When using MorphOS 1.4 you'll only able to use
the @{"CDTV extensions" link "FAQSRAW"}.@{par}

There are a few "restrictions". Sounds bad, but it's logic:@{par}

The hardware password isn't available, because we don't have any MMKeyboard hardware.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSHotkeys" "How is the hotkey standard working?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "How is the hotkey standard working?"}

Very simple! Everyone knows hot it's working! Well, most Amiga users aren't aware of the features
supported by our hotkey system.@{par}

@{b}Please not that MMKeyboard is supporting this standard, but to fit in all the new keys and all
options I made many enhancements and of course shortcuts. These are only available within MMKeyboard.@{ub}@{par}

All keys are defined as normal text. These can be found within commodity toolTypes (e.g. MMKeyboardServer) and
string input gadget with gadget user interface (e.g. MMKeyboard).@{par}

So to specify an "a" just enter an "a"! All keys that never produce any output can be used by
inserting the entire name.@{par}

These keys are : "F1", "F2", "F3", "F4", "F5", "F6", "F7", "F8", "F9", "F10",, "SPACE", "BACKSPACE",
"ENTER", "RETURN", "DELETE", "ESC", "HELP", "TAB", "UP", "DOWN", "LEFT" and "RIGHT".@{par}

Hey! There missing keys! Yes! These keys are known as qualifier. A qualifier is a key that only
works in combination with a normal key.@{par}

"LSHIFT", "RSHIFT", "CAPSLOCK", "CONTROL", "LALT", "RALT", "LCOMMAND" and "RCOMMAND".@{par}

There are additional pseudo qualifiers available: "NUMERICPAD", "REPEAT", "MULTIBROADCAST",
"INTERRUPT", "MIDBUTTON", "RBUTTON" and "LEFTBUTTON". "NUMERICPAD" is only present for key on the
numeric pad. "REPEAT" causes that only repeating keys are causing action. The button qualifiers are
representing the three mouse buttons. "MULTIBROADCAST" is sending a key into all windows even if
they're disabled, so you should have a good reason to use it.@{par}

Key groups are available, too: "SHIFT", "CAPS", "ALT". Using a group will require at least one of
the keys with in the group is required. When using "CAPS", then one shift or the capslock key is
required to activate the hotkey.@{par}

So far the most definitions are known. Now the secret part. The normal qualifiers may be used with
an additional dash in front. These look like this: "-LSHIFT", "-RSHIFT", "-CAPSLOCK", "-CONTROL",
"-LALT", "-RALT", "-LCOMMAND", "-RCOMMAND" "-NUMERICPAD", "-REPEAT", "-MULTIBROADCAST",
"-INTERRUPT", "-MIDBUTTON", "-RBUTTON" and "-LEFTBUTTON". When using such qualifier it it not
important for the hotkey. It doesn't matter if the dash qualifier is pressed or not.@{par}

By default hotkeys are only acting on key press. When using the keyword "UPSTROKE" the hotkey is
acting on key release only. The version with a leading dash is forcing the hotkey to become active
on key down and key up.@{par}

 Examples:@{par}

"control lalt help" -> Only these three keys.@{par}

"control alt help" -> Only these three keys. Which and how many alt keys are used isn't important.@{par}

"control alt -lshift help" -> Like the example above, but the left shift key may be pressed without
effecting the result.@{par}

@{MS "Here a small overview on MMKeyboards internal features:"}

"LSHIFT", "RSHIFT", "CAPSLOCK", "CONTROL", "LALT", "RALT", "LCOMMAND", "RCOMMAND". "MIDBUTTON",
"RBUTTON" and "LEFTBUTTON" may be used a normal hot key. This is done by entering a "+" before it's
name. MMKeyboard is handling the "+Qualifier" as normal key. Please note that a ghost qualifier will be
created for +Qualifier. e.g. "+CONTROL" -> "CONTROL +CONTROL" This is required, because by pressing the
control key the system creates a control qualifier for the control key.@{par}

"lalt +ralt" -> LALT is the normal Qualifier and RALT a normal key.@{par}

"lshift rshift +leftbutton" -> Not very handy, but pressing both shift keys and the left mouse
button will start the action.@{par}

It's possible to enter the names by a shorter version. In the most cases it's required to enter the
first chars of each name part:@{par}

"la" -> "LALT"@{par}
"+ls" -> "+LSHIFT"@{par}
"-RC" -> "-RCOMMAND"@{par}
"CT" -> "CONTROL"@{par}



@endnode
@node "FAQSRAW" "What are rawkey codes?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What are rawkey codes?"}

Rawkeys are the keycodes send by the keyboard. The are not equal to ascii!!@{par}

The value given by the table are only 100% valid for the amithlon and the
MorphOS version. INSERT, PAGE_UP, PAGE_DOWN, F11 and F12 are transfered with a
special message and without translation to the amiga standard. You need to remap
the keys by using the macro @{"IEvent" link "MacrosIEvent"} command if you
want to use them with the commodities.library or another tool.@{par}

The right column isn't used in the Amithlon version, because the keyboard.device
is filtering the them.@{par}

To read the table use the following example: The key "A" has the hex code 20. Thie means
column 2 line 0.@{par}

@{code}

    |    0   |    1   |    2   |    3    |    4   |    5   |    6   |    7   |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   ~    |        |        | euro    |        |        |  LEFT  |        |
 0  |        |   Q    |   A    | extra   | SPACE  |   F1   |        | HOME   |
    |   `    |        |        | shift   |        |        |  SHIFT |        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   !    |        |        |         | BACK-  |        |  RIGHT |        |
 1  |        |   W    |   S    |    Z    | SPACE  |   F2   |        | END    |
    |   1    |        |        |         |        |        |  SHIFT |        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   \@    |        |        |         |        |        |  CAPS  | CDTV   |
 2  |        |   E    |   D    |    X    |  TAB   |   F3   |        |        |
    |   2    |        |        |         |        |        |  LOCK  | STOP   |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   #    |        |        |         |  NP    |        |        | CDTV   |
 3  |        |   R    |   F    |    C    |        |   F4   |  CTRL  | PLAY/  |
    |   3    |        |        |         | ENTER  |        |        | PAUSE  |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   $    |        |        |         |        |        |  LEFT  | CDTV   |
 4  |        |   T    |   G    |    V    | RETURN |   F5   |        |        |
    |   4    |        |        |         |        |        |  ALT   | PREV   |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   %    |        |        |         |        |        |  RIGHT | CDTV   |
 5  |        |   Y    |   H    |    B    |  ESC   |   F6   |        |        |
    |   5    |        |        |         |        |        |  ALT   | NEXT   |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   ^    |        |        |         |        |        |  LEFT  | CDTV   |
 6  |        |   U    |   J    |    N    |  DEL   |   F7   |        |        |
    |   6    |        |        |         |        |        |  AMIGA | REW    |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   &    |        |        |         |        |        |  RIGHT | CDTV   |
 7  |        |   I    |   K    |    M    |  INS   |   F8   |        |        |
    |   7    |        |        |         |        |        |  AMIGA | FF     |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   *    |        |        |    <    |        |        |  MOUSE | Reset  |
 8  |        |   O    |   L    |         |  PAGE  |   F9   |        | Warn   |
    |   8    |        |        |    ,    |   UP   |        |  LEFT  |        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   (    |        |   :    |    >    |        |        |  MOUSE |        |
 9  |        |   P    |        |         |  PAGE  |   F10  |        |        |
    |   9    |        |   ;    |    .    |  DOWN  |        |  RIGHT |        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   )    |   {    |   "    |    ?    |   NP   |   NP   |  MOUSE |        |
 A  |        |        |        |         |        |        |        |        |
    |   0    |   [    |   '    |    /    |   -    |   (    |  CENTER|        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   _    |   }    | euro   |         |        |   NP   |        |        |
 B  |        |        | extra  |         |  F11   |        |        |        |
    |   -    |   ]    | ret    |         |        |   )    |        |        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   +    |        |        |   NP    |  CRSR  |   NP   |        |        |
 C  |        |        |        |         |        |        |        |        |
    |   =    |        |        |   .     |   UP   |   /    |        |        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   |    |   NP   |   NP   |   NP    |  CRSR  |   NP   |        |        |
 D  |        |        |        |         |        |        |        |        |
    |   \\    |   1    |   4    |   7     |  DOWN  |   *    |        |        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |        |   NP   |   NP   |   NP    |  CRSR  |   NP   | PAUSE  |        |
 E  |        |        |        |         |        |        |        |        |
    |        |   2    |   5    |   8     |  RIGHT |   +    | BREAK  |        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   NP   |   NP   |   NP   |   NP    |  CRSR  |        |        |        |
 F  |        |        |        |         |        |  HELP  |  F12   |        |
