@{"Keyboard editor" link "KeEd"} @{"Password set-up" link "Pass"} @{"Password GUI Set-up" link "PaGU"}
@{"PIC Set-up" link "PICC"}

@endnode
@node "EditName" "Hotkey Set-up - Name"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Name"}

Here you can specify a special name for the hotkey.@{par}

The name will only be used for the @{"Keylist" link "MASTLIST"}!

@endnode
@node "EditHoKe" "Hotkey Set-up - HotKey"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "HotKey"}

If you want to set-up a multimedia hot key, just press the key or key combination you
want!@{par}

By using the PopUp Gadget you're are able to specify normal system hotkeys like CONTROL ALT
HELP.@{par}

Of course it's possible to enter all hotkeys by hand, but you should aware that any wrong part will
be removed!

There are a few "pseudo" keys that require Manuel input:

@{MS "KBReset"}

This @{"command" link "EditComm"} will be used only when resetting the amiga by keyboard. Qualifier
(Shift, Alt, ...) are not allowed. Please note that the reset is delayed until the last KBReset
hotkey is executed or the @{"maximum delay time" link "FAQSResetHandler"} is over. If you're using
two or more KBReset hotkeys then you must be aware that the second @{"command" link "EditComm"}
won't be started until the first is done. Avoid starting programs in @{"WBMode" link "EditExTy"},
because they're started asynchrony and don't delay the reset.

@{MS "KBPlug"}

If you plug in a keyboard this @{"command" link "EditComm"} will be executed. Normaly such command
is useless, but if you're switching your keyboard between PC and Amiga you're able to play a sample
or something like that.

@endnode
@node "EditTask" "MMKeyboard Set-up - Task Name"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Task Name"}

Here you can specify a task name for the hotkey.@{par}

Let's say you're using two music player. One for CD and one for MP3. The problem is that there is
only one "play" key on your keyboard. By using this gadget it's possible to start different hotkey
for different applications by using the same key.@{par}

It's required to enter the task name here. In normal cases this is the program name without any
path! Workbench windows are listening to "workbench". Golded requires a "golded" within this gadget.
The string will be compared last byte first and the case isn't important at all.@{par}

When using the popup window, to select an available task, task names containing "/" and/or ":" are reduced
to their filename. This may not be correct in some cases, so it may be required to enter the full
string by hand.@{par}

@{b}The task selection window is only able to display running tasks at the time of opening.
Some of the displayed tasks are not useful, because in normal case they never open a window
(only error report). These task are devices "#?.device" and dos drives "df0" in the first place!
It's not possible to filter them, so don't ask for it. MMKeyboard is not able to detect if a
program is able to open a window. E.g. MMKeyboardServer is only able to open error requests.@{ub}@{par}

@{b}Note: The whole task stuff isn't respecting the programming guidelines. I tried to
avoid any risks, but shit happens. When leaving the task field clear for all hotkeys the "illegal"
stuff isn't used at all and MMKeyboard is working 100% compatible again. The task popup window is
probably the most significant hack, because MMKeyboard is scanning the exec.library internal data.@{ub}@{par}
@endnode
@node "EditExTy" "Hotkey Set-up - Execute type"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Execute type"}

This gadget allows to set-up what type of command is specified in the @{"command" link "EditComm"} gadget.@{par}

Currently "CLI", "WB", "Key Command", "Arexx" and @{"Macro" link "Macros"} are available.@{par}

@endnode
@node "EditStac" "Hotkey Set-up - Stack"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Stack"}

This gadget specifies the stack for the @{"command" link "EditComm"}.

@endnode
@node "EditComm" "Hotkey Set-up - Command"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Command"}

The contents of this gadget depends on the @{"execute type" link "EditExTy"}.@{par}

@{MS "CLI / WB"}

Path and command name of the command you want to execute.

@{MS "Key Command"}

This gadget contains a new key combination. Please note that key groups like "SHIFT" are not
allowed. It's required to specify the key. So define "LSHIFT", "RSHIFT" or "CAPSLOCK" insteat.@{par}

MMKeyboard is using the qualifier without any modifications. So a "CONTROL LALT HELP" is used even
if the user is pressing the shift key! Sometimes it may be useful to let the user qualifier through.
Let's say you want the Help key as a replacement for an "a". It's required that you're able to type
a "A" (shift) or an "ć" (alt). The "-" version of a qualifier in indicating that the specified
qualifier is path through. In our case the key command looks like this: "-LSHIFT -RSHIFT -LALT -RALT
-RCOMMAND -RCOMMAND -CONTROL -CAPSLOCK a".

@{MS "Command"}

MMKeyboard is supporting a several @{"commands" link "Macros"} for hotkey usage.@{par}

@endnode
@node "EditCuDi" "Hotkey Set-up - Current Directory"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Current Directory"}

If you want to change the current directory for the @{"command" link "EditComm"}, then put it in
here.

@endnode
@node "EditOuFi" "Hotkey Set-up - Output File"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Output File"}

The output of the command can be redirected by using this gadget.

@endnode
@node "EditOkOk" "Hotkey Set-up - Use"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Use"}

The hotkey settings will be used and the edit window will be closed.

@endnode
@node "EditCanc" "Hotkey Set-up - Cancel"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Cancel"}

Closes the edit window! All changes will be rejected.

@endnode

@node "GeLw" "The List Selection Window"
@toc "EDIT"

@{MS "The List Selection Window"}

This window allows to select a specific entry of a given list.@{par}

Just use the cursor keys and the return key to select the desired entry. Of course is
it possible to select the entry by double clicking an entry.@{par}

@endnode

@node "KeCh" "MMKeyboard: Global Set-Up"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Global Set-Up"}

Just select vendor and keyboard you're using. If your keyboard isn't listed use the
@{"keyboard editor" link "KeEd"} (menu) to create your own set-up.@{par}

@{code}
@{JCENTER}@{"Vendor List" link "KECHVELI"}
@{"Keyboard List" link "KECHKELI"}
@{"Show keys" link "KECHSHKE"}
@{"Show Qualifiers" link "KECHSHQU"}
@{"Show Tasks" link "KECHTASK"}
@{"Show Command Types" link "KECHTYPE"}
@{"Show Commands" link "KECHSHCO"}
@{"Show Command Qualifier" link "KECHCMDQ"}
@{"Show Command Path" link "KECHCMDP"}
@{"Save" link "KECHSAVE"}
@{"Use" link "KECHOKOK"}
@{"Cancel" link "KECHCANC"}

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{"Main Window" link "MAST"} @{"Edit Window" link "EDIT"} @{"Global Set-Up" link "KECH"}
@{"Keyboard editor" link "KEED"} @{"Password set-up" link "PASS"} @{"Password GUI Set-up" link "PAGU"}
@{"PIC Set-up" link "PICC"}

@endnode
@node "KECHVELI" "Global Set-Up - Vendor List"
@toc "KECH"

@{MS "Vendor List"}

This list contains all supported vendors.@{par}

@{b}If your keyboard vendor isn't supported, then use the @{"keyboard editor" link "KeEd"} to create
a set-up for it.@{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "KECHKELI" "Global Set-Up - Keyboard List"
@toc "KECH"

@{MS "Keyboard List"}

This list contains all supported keyboards created by the selected vendor.@{par}

@{b}If your keyboard isn't supported, use the @{"keyboard editor" link "KeEd"} to create
a set-up for it.@{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "KECHSHKE" "Global Set-Up - Show Keys"
@toc "KECH"

@{MS "Show Keys"}

This switch allows to configure the main window hot key list.@{par}

If this switch is enabled the key names will be displayed in the list.@{par}

@endnode
@node "KECHSHQU" "Global Set-Up - Show Qualifiers"
@toc "KECH"

@{MS "Show Qualifiers"}

This switch allows to configure the main window hot key list.@{par}

If @{"show keys" link "KECHSHKE"} is enabled, you can turn the related
qualifiers on and off by using this gadget.@{par}

@endnode
@node "KECHTASK" "Global Set-Up - Show Tasks"
@toc "KECH"

@{MS "Show Tasks"}

This switch allows to configure the main window hot key list.@{par}

It may be useful to show the hotkey related tasks within the main list, so here
is the switch to display them.@{par}

@endnode
@node "KECHTYPE" "Global Set-Up - Show Command Types"
@toc "KECH"

@{MS "Show Command Types"}

This switch allows to configure the main window hot key list.@{par}

The type of execution performed for a hotkey will be displayed within the main
list by activating this gadget.@{par}

@endnode
@node "KECHSHCO" "Global Set-Up - Show Commands"
@toc "KECH"

@{MS "Show Commands"}

This switch allows to configure the main window hot key list.@{par}

If you want to see what command is bond to a key combination, turn on this
gadget and it will be displayed within the main list.@{par}

@endnode
@node "KECHCMDQ" "Global Set-Up - Show Command Qualifier"
@toc "KECH"

@{MS "Show Command Qualifier"}

This switch allows to configure the main window hot key list.@{par}

If @{"show commands" link "KECHSHCO"} is enabled and the command type is a key, then this switch will
display the key qualifier, too.

@endnode
@node "KECHCMDP" "Global Set-Up - Show Command Path"
@toc "KECH"

@{MS "Show Command Path"}

This switch allows to configure the main window hot key list.@{par}

If @{"show commands" link "KECHSHCO"} is enabled and the command type is a file
based type, then this switch will force MMKeyboard to display the full command
path.

@endnode
@node "KECHSAVE" "Global Set-Up - Save"
@toc "KECH"

@{MS "Save"}

The hotkey settings will be saved and the edit window will be closed.@{par}

@endnode
@node "KECHOKOK" "Global Set-Up - Use"
@toc "KECH"

@{MS "Use"}

The hotkey settings will be used and the edit window will be closed.@{par}

@endnode
@node "KECHCANC" "Global Set-Up - Cancel"
@toc "KECH"

@{MS "Cancel"}

Closes the keyboard set-up window! All changes will be rejected.@{par}

@endnode

@node "SYSS" "MMKeyboard: System Specific Set-up"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "System Specific Set-up"}

Depending on the used System this window is providing gadgets to configure the
keyboard interface.@{par}

@{code}
@{JCENTER}@{"CapsLock" link "SYSSCAPS"}
@{"Alt<>Amiga Swap" link "SYSSALTA"}
@{"Menu PopUp" link "SYSSMEPO"}
@{"Insert" link "SYSSINSE"}
@{"RControl" link "SYSSRCTL"}
@{"Mouse Buttons" link "SYSSMOUS"}
@{"Mouse Wheels" link "SYSSWHEL"}
@{"Use" link "SYSSOKOK"}
@{"Cancel" link "SYSSCANC"}

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{"Main Window" link "MAsT"} @{"Edit Window" link "Edit"} @{"Global Set-Up" link "KeCh"}
@{"Keyboard editor" link "KeEd"} @{"Password set-up" link "Pass"} @{"Password GUI Set-up" link "PaGU"}
@{"PIC Set-up" link "PICC"}

@endnode
@node "SYSSCAPS" "System Specific Set-up - CapsLock"
@toc "SYSS"

@{MS "CapsLock"}

This gadget allows to deactivate the CapsLock key.

@endnode
@node "SYSSALTA" "System Specific Set-up - Alt<>Amiga Swap"
@toc "SYSS"

@{MS "Alt<>Amiga Swap"}

@{b}This gadget is only available in the Amithlon version!@{ub}@{par}

This is a special feature! As you may have noticed the windows keys aren't in
the same positions like the command keys on an Amiga keyboard! On Amiga
keyboards the Command keys are next to the space key, but on the windows version
that's the position of the ALT keys.@{par}

Just turn this feature on to swap the ALT and WIN keys. Don't forget to swap the
key caps on your keyboard. This may be a good time to kill the windows logo on
the keys.@{par}

@{b}This feature does not effect the reset combination! If you want to reset
Amithlon by pressing control RCommand LCommand you need to define a hotkey
("Control Klcommand Krcommand") and execute a reset tool.@{ub}

@endnode
@node "SYSSINSE" "System Specific Set-up - Insert"
@toc "SYSS"

@{MS "Insert"}

@{b}This gadget is only available in the Amithlon version!@{ub}@{par}

By default the help key is located on the MenuPop key (next to the right control key). This isn't very handy,
so here you can define the help key onto the insert key.@{par}

@endnode
@node "SYSSMEPO" "System Specific Set-up - Menu PopUp"
@toc "SYSS"

@{MS "Menu PopUp"}

@{b}This gadget is only available in the Amithlon version!@{ub}@{par}

By default the help key is located on this key. This isn't very handy! By using this gadget you can choose
between:@{par}

@endnode
@node "SYSSRCTL" "System Specific Set-up - RControl"
@toc "SYSS"

@{MS "RControl"}

@{b}This gadget is only available in the Amithlon version!@{ub}@{par}

By default this key is used as second control key.@{par}

@endnode
@node "SYSSMOUS" "System Specific Set-up - Mouse Buttons"
@toc "SYSS"

@{MS "Mouse Buttons"}

@{b}This gadget is only available in the Amithlon version!@{ub}@{par}

Here you can specify which additional mouse button you want to use as Multimedia Hotkey.@{par}

@{b}To undo the previous setup it's required to reboot Amithlon after changing this gadget.@{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "SYSSWHEL" "System Specific Set-up - Mouse Wheels"
@toc "SYSS"

@{MS "Mouse Wheels"}

@{b}This gadget is only available in the Amithlon version!@{ub}@{par}

Here you can specify how to handle the mouse wheels.@{par}

@{b}To undo the previous setup it's required to reboot Amithlon after changing this gadget.@{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "SYSSOKOK" "System Specific Set-up - Use"
@toc "SYSS"

@{MS "Use"}

The current settings will be used and the window get's closed.@{par}

@endnode
@node "SYSSCANC" "System Specific Set-up - Cancel"
@toc "SYSS"

@{MS "Cancel"}

Closes the set-up window! All changes will be rejected.@{par}

@endnode

@node "KeEd" "MMKeyboard: Keyboard Editor"
@toc "KeCh"

@{MS "Keyboard Editor"}

This small editor allows to define key names for the new multimedia keyboards!@{PAR}

It's not required to create such names, but look at the following example:@{PAR}

"CONTROL ALT $8334"  (The hex value is just an example)@{PAR}

Which hotkey is used? MMKeyboard internally only uses these hex values, and you are able to define
these Hotkeys by pressing them, but if you later take look on your configuration it's not very handy to
deal with hex values and identify the key. After 2 Minutes key set-up the example looks much better:@{PAR}

"CONTROL ALT PLAY"@{PAR}

@{b}Before creating your own keyboard setting, you should check if it's already present in the
"Presets/MMKeyboard/Keyboards/" drawer of your installation. Just try to load and see for your self.@{ub}@{PAR}

The keyboard editor is very easy to use:@{PAR}

1. Press the multimedia key you want to add.@{PAR}
2. Select the name by using the pop up gadget or enter the name by using the input field.@{PAR}
3. If there are more multimedia keys to add then proceed with 1.@{PAR}
4. Use the @{"save gadget" link "KeEdKeSa"} to save the keyboard settings.@{PAR}
5. Send me your configuration to include it into my archive. (-8
@{code}
@{MS "These are the gadgets available in the keyboard editor:"}
@{JCENTER}@{"Vendor Name" link "KeEdVeNa"}
@{"Keyboard Name" link "KeEdKBNa"}
@{"Author Name" link "KeEdKBAu"}

@{"Keyboard List" link "KeEdKeLi"}
@{"New..." link "KeEdKeNe"}
@{"Load..." link "KeEdKeLo"}
@{"Save..." link "KeEdKeSa"}

@{"Remove" link "KeEdKeRe"}
@{"Remove All..." link "KeEdKeRA"}

@{"Name" link "KeEdKeNa"}
@{"Value" link "KeEdKeVa"}

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{"Main Window" link "MAsT"} @{"Edit Window" link "Edit"} @{"Global Set-Up" link "KeCh"}
@{"Keyboard editor" link "KeEd"} @{"Password set-up" link "Pass"} @{"Password GUI Set-up" link "PaGU"}
@{"PIC Set-up" link "PICC"}

@endnode
@node "KeEdVeNa" "Keyboard Editor - Vendor Name"
@toc "KeEd"

@{MS "Vendor Name"}

This gadget defines the vendor name of the keyboard. Please make sure the name is correct, because
MMKeyboard requires it to group all keyboards of the same vendor.

@endnode
@node "KeEdKBNa" "Keyboard Editor -  Keyboard Name"
@toc "KeEd"

@{MS "Keyboard Name"}

This input gadget holds the keyboard name. Please note that the name must be very specific. It's a
good idea to use the identification label at the back of your keyboard.

@endnode
@node "KeEdKBAu" "Keyboard Editor -  Author Name"
@toc "KeEd"

@{MS "Author Name"}

Here you can specify your name.

@endnode
@node "KeEdKeLi" "Keyboard Editor - Key List"
@toc "KeEd"
@{MS "Key List"}

This listview displays all defined keys by name. It's possible browse by mouse, mouse wheel or keyboard (CRSR
UP, CRSR DOWN and RETURN).@{PAR}

To add a key just press it! An existing key can be selected by pressing it, too.@{PAR}

@{b}It's only possible to add non standard windows keys! Keys like F11 or Page_Up are
predefined.@{ub}

@endnode
@node "KeEdKeNe" "Keyboard Editor - New..."
@toc "KeEd"
@{MS "New"}

@{b}This gadget is obsolete! You can simply create new entries by pushing the
multimedia keys right within the editor.@{ub}

@endnode
@node "KeEdKeLo" "Keyboard Editor - Load..."
@toc "KeEd"

@{MS "Load..."}

Here you can specify a keyboard file to load.@{PAR}

@endnode
@node "KeEdKeSa" "Keyboard Editor - Save..."
@toc "KeEd"

@{MS "Save..."}

Here you can save the current keyboard settings.@{par}

@endnode
@node "KeEdKeRe" "Keyboard Editor - Remove"
@toc "KeEd"

@{MS "Remove"}

This button deletes the selected key.@{PAR}

@{b}Under normal circumstances it's not wise to delete any key, because the only keys you can
add are non Amiga keys and it's not possible to enter one key twice. Well, some keyboards may
report ghost keys, so these keys can be removed.@{ub}

@endnode
@node "KeEdKeRa" "Keyboard Editor - Remove All..."
@toc "KeEd"

@{MS "RemoveAll..."}

Here you can delete the entire key list.@{PAR}

@endnode
@node "KeEdKeNa" "Keyboard Editor - Name"
@toc "KeEd"

@{MS "Name"}

This input gadget allows to specify the name of the selected key. Spaces and several other keys are
not allowed.@{PAR}

@endnode
@node "KeEdKeVa" "Keyboard Editor - Value"
@toc "KeEd"

@{MS "Value"}

This little gadget just displays the current key value and is for (my) information only.@{PAR}

@endnode

@node "PICC" "MMKeyboard: PIC Set-up"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "PIC Set-up"}

@{b}This window is not available when using Amithlon!@{ub}@{par}

This window allows to set-up the PIC configuration by selecting the features.@{par}
@{code}
@{MS "Password Options"}
@{JCENTER}@{"Password Mode" link "PICCPass"}
@{"Password HotKey" link "PICCPaHo"}
@{MS "Power Options"}
@{JCENTER}@{"Power Mode" link "PICCPoMo"}
@{"Power Key" link "PICCPoKe"}
@{MS "Key Options"}
@{JCENTER}@{"Screen Flip" link "PICCScre"}
@{"PrintScr" link "PICCPrin"}
@{"Break" link "PICCBrea"}
@{"RightCTRL" link "PICCRCTR"}
@{"Home" link "PICCHome"}
@{"End" link "PICCEndd"}
@{"Page Up" link "PICCPaUp"}
@{"Page Down" link "PICCPaDo"}
@{"Num Lock" link "PICCNuLo"}
@{"Caps Lock" link "PICCCaLo"}
@{"Help" link "PICCHELP"}
@{"Alt<>Win Swap" link "PICCALTT"}
@{MS "PIC Configuration"}
@{JCENTER}@{"Set-up PIC Configuration..." link "PICCConf"}
@{"Value" link "PICCValu"}

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{"Main Window" link "MAsT"} @{"Edit Window" link "Edit"} @{"Global Set-Up" link "KeCh"}
@{"Keyboard editor" link "KeEd"} @{"Password set-up" link "Pass"} @{"Password GUI Set-up" link "PaGU"}
@{"PIC Set-up" link "PICC"}

@endnode
@node "PICCPass" "PIC Set-up - Password Mode"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Password Mode"}

This gadget turn on the password request of the PIC.@{par}

The real keyboard access is denied until the correct password is entered.@{par}

Editing the password by using delete, backspace or the cursor keys is not possible! If you make a
mistake just press "RETURN" and re-enter the password.@{par}

It's not possible to reset your Amiga by keyboard during password request.@{par}

@{b}Warning: This is a real hardware password! There is no back door or something like that!
Make sure your password is correct *before* enabling it! If not, it will be required to reprogram
the PIC by using an external PIC programmer!@{par}

The password is working independent! The @{"password enable" link "PassActi"} switch only enables
the GUI! After setting this configuration the password will be required even when using a boot disc!
The Amiga is only able to display a password GUI! The password itself is checked within the
hardware!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PICCPaHo" "PIC Set-up - Password Hotkey"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Password Hotkey"}

This gadget turns on the password hotkey.@{par}

"ScrLock" (re)starts the password protection. This is very useful when leaving your Amiga alone for a
while. You should read the @{"password mode" link "PICCPass"} section, before turning this on.@{par}

@{b}Disabling this gadget allows you to use the key like any other multimedia key!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PICCPoMo" "PIC Set-up - Power Mode"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Power Mode"}

@{b}For this feature @{"additional hardware" link "FAQSPICPowerSW"} is required!@{ub}@{par}

By using this useful feature it's possible to shut down and restart your Amiga by keyboard.@{par}

Make sure you defined the @{"Power Key" link "PICCPoKe"} when using this!@{par}

To shut down the Amiga just press "RAMIGA" and the @{"Power Key" link "PICCPoKe"}. A single second
keystroke (@{"Power Key" link "PICCPoKe"} only) restarts your system.@{par}

@{b}The power mode is full reset handler compatible! This means any application using a reset
handler has at least 10 seconds time before the system shuts down! If there isn't a reset handler
running there is no additional delay!@{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "PICCPoKe" "PIC Set-up - Power HotKey"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Power HotKey"}

@{b}For this feature @{"additional hardware" link "FAQSPICPowerSW"} is required.@{ub}@{par}

Just press the desired key you want to use as power key. Remember that you are no longer able to use
"RAMIGA" in any conjunction with this key, because the system shut down when using this combination.

@endnode
@node "PICCScre" "PIC Set-up - Screen Flip"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Screen Flip"}

When activated pressing the "Menu PopUp" key (between RWin & RControl key) the amiga receives a
"LAMIGA M" (ScreenFlip).@{par}

@{b}Disabling this gadget allows you to use the key like any other multimedia key!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PICCPrin" "PIC Set-up - PrintScr"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "PrintScr"}

Pressing the PrintScreen key (aka PrtScr, Druck) the keyboard sends a "RAMIGA P"!
This is the standard Amiga key combination for printing.@{par}

@{b}Disabling this gadget allows you to use the key like any other multimedia key!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PICCBrea" "PIC Set-up - Break"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Break"}

Pressing the break key the amiga receives a "CONTROL C"! This combination causes
shell programs to quit.@{par}

@{b}Disabling this gadget allows you to use the key like any other multimedia key!@{ub}


@endnode
@node "PICCRCTr" "PIC Set-up - Right CTRL"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Right CTRL"}

The right control key will act as a normal control key.@{par}

@{b}Disabling this gadget allows you to use the key like any other multimedia key!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PICCHome" "PIC Set-up - Home"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Home"}

Pressing this key causes a "SHIFT CRSR LEFT".@{par}

@{b}Disabling this gadget allows you to use the key like any other multimedia key!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PICCEndd" "PIC Set-up - End"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "End"}

Pressing this key causes a "SHIFT CRSR RIGHT".@{par}

@{b}Disabling this gadget allows you to use the key like any other multimedia key!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PICCPaUp" "PIC Set-up - Page Up"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Page Up"}

Pressing this key causes a "SHIFT CRSR UP"!@{par}

@{b}Disabling this gadget allows you to use the key like any other multimedia key!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PICCPaDo" "PIC Set-up - Page Down"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Page Down"}

Pressing this key causes a "SHIFT CRSR DOWN".@{par}

@{b}Disabling this gadget allows you to use the key like any other multimedia key!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PICCNuLo" "PIC Set-up - NumLock"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "NumLock"}

By default this gadget allows to toggle the numpad lock mode.@{par}

There is no further use, but some keyboard may require such feature.@{par}

Just turn it off to get the normal Amiga NumLock key!@{par}

@endnode
@node "PICCCaLo" "PIC Set-up - CapsLock"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "CapsLock"}

By default this gadget allows to toggle the capslock mode.@{par}

@{b}Disabling this gadget allows you to use the key like any other multimedia key!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PICCHelp" "PIC Set-up - Help"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Help"}

By default the "insert" key is used as "Help" key, because on Amiga insert is useless.
You are able to use "F12" and/or "Insert" as "help" key@{par}

@{b}Any unused key is available as multimedia key.@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PICCALTT" "PIC Set-up - Alt<>Amiga Swap"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Alt<>Amiga Swap"}

This is a special feature! As you may have noticed the windows keys aren't in
the same positions like the command keys on an Amiga keyboard! On Amiga
keyboards the command keys are next to the space key, but on the windows version
that's the position of the ALT keys.@{par}

Just turn this feature on to swap the ALT and WIN keys. Don't forget to swap the
key caps on your keyboard. This may be a good time to kill the windows logo on
the keys.@{par}

@{b}After swapping the keys the Command key is ALWAYS next to the space key!
Even the PIC internal menu and the power mode are using the new key
positions!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PICCConf" "PIC Set-up - Set-up PIC Configuration..."
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Set-up PIC Configuration..."}

After skipping safety requester you'll guided through the PIC Configuration.@{par}

@{b}It's required that the keyboard is working normal. This means no wrong or repeated chars. This
set-up is only changing functions. If your interface isn't working at, then all this set-up won't have any
effect. By using this set-up anyway you risk a total configuration damage, which may result in an
unknown password.@{ub}@{par}

Important: The predefined password is "amiga", but this default value may not be writing by your PIC programming
tool. It makes sense to change the password to "amiga" once before playing around with the set-up. Even if you don't
want to use the password you're able to enter it even if it's activated by accident.@{par}

If you're asking your self, why the PIC set-up is so stupid, then you should read @{"this" link "FAQSPICStupidSetup"}.@{par}

Follow the configuration menu word by word. If you make a mistake during the password enter process,
then just press "RETURN" and select password again. The PIC configuration itself is auto detecting any
error and forces the user to re-enter the data without telling him.@{par}

@endnode
@node "PICCValu" "PIC Set-up - Configuration Value"
@toc "PICC"

@{MS "Configuration Value"}

This is the configuration value for the PIC when using the settings made by using this window!@{par}

@{b}It's only useful when doing the PIC Set-up without the @{"set-up window" link "PICC"}. It's for
experts only. If you don't know what I am talking about then don't think about this gadget.@{ub}@{par}

@endnode

@node "Macros" "Macros"

@{MS "Macros"}

Macros are small functions, which can be specified as action by a simple
selection.@{par}

@{JCenter}
The following Macros are supported:@{par}

@{b}Screen Operations@{ub}@{par}

@{"ScreenNext" link "MacrosScreenNext"}*@{par}
@{"ScreenPrev" link "MacrosScreenPrev"}*@{par}
@{"WBToFront" link "MacrosWBToFront"}*@{par}

@{b}Window Operations@{ub}@{par}

@{"WindowBottomLeft" link "MacrosWindowBottomLeft"}*@{par}
@{"WindowBottomRight" link "MacrosWindowBottomRight"}*@{par}
@{"WindowCenter" link "MacrosWindowCenter"}*@{par}
@{"WindowClose" link "MacrosWindowClose"}@{par}
@{"WindowControl" link "MacrosWindowControl"}*@{par}
@{"WindowMaximise" link "MacrosWindowMaximise"}*@{par}
@{"WindowMinimise" link "MacrosWindowMinimise"}*@{par}
@{"WindowMove" link "MacrosWindowMove"}*@{par}
@{"WindowNext" link "MacrosWindowNext"}*@{par}
@{"WindowPrev" link "MacrosWindowPrev"}*@{par}
@{"WindowToBack" link "MacrosWindowToBack"}*@{par}
@{"WindowToFront" link "MacrosWindowToFront"}*@{par}
@{"WindowTopLeft" link "MacrosWindowTopLeft"}*@{par}
@{"WindowTopRight" link "MacrosWindowTopRight"}*@{par}
@{"WindowZip" link "MacrosWindowZip"}*@{par}

@{"ReqOk" link "MacrosReqOk"}*@{par}
@{"ReqCancel" link "MacrosReqCancel"}@{par}

@{b}Mouse Operations@{ub}@{par}

@{"MouseClick" link "MacrosMouseClick"}@{par}
@{"MouseMove" link "MacrosMouseMove"}@{par}

@{b}System Operations@{ub}@{par}

@{"ColdReboot" link "MacrosColdReboot"}@{par}
@{"WarmReboot" link "MacrosWarmReboot"}@{par}

@{b}Clipboard Operations@{ub}@{par}

@{"Cut" link "MacrosCut"}@{par}
@{"Copy" link "MacrosCopy"}@{par}
@{"Paste" link "MacrosPaste"}@{par}

@{b}Miscellaneous@{ub}@{par}

@{"IEvent" link "MacrosIEvent"}@{par}
@{"Eject" link "MacrosEject"}@{par}
@{"IRComSend" link "MacrosIRcomSend"}@{par}

@{JLEFT}
@{b}* Please note that the usage of these macros may cause trouble, because they ignore several
system programming rules.@{ub}

@endnode
@node "MacrosArguments" "Macros - The Arguments"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "The Argumente"}

The arguments follow the same rules like the command arguments under AmigaDos.
Please refer your dos manual for further information.@{par}

If you want to specify spaces within strings it's required to enclose the string
with brackets.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosScreenNext" "Macros - ScreenNext"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "ScreenNext"}

This function forces the next screen to front.

@endnode
@node "MacrosScreenPrev" "Macros - ScreenPrev"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "ScreenPrev"}

This function forces the previous screen to front.

@endnode
@node "MacrosWBToFront" "Macros - WBToFront"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WBToFront"}

By using this command you force the workbench screen to front. (LCOMMAND n).@{par}

This command requires no @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}!@{par}

Example:@{par}

WBToFront@{par}

Creates a "LCOMMAND n" input event.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowBottomLeft" "Macros - WindowBottomLeft"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowBottomLeft"}

The active window will be moved into the left bottom edge of the screen.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowBottomRight" "Macros - WindowBottomRight"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowBottomRight"}

The active window will be moved into the right bottom edge of the screen.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowCenter" "Macros - WindowCenter"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowCenter"}

The active window will centered.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowClose" "Macros - WindowClose"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowClose"}

The active window will close. Of course the window must have a close button.

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowControl" "Macros - WindowControl"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowControl"}

@{b}This macro is only available when using MorphOS!@{ub}@{par}

By using this command you can hide and unhide windows.@{par}

HIDE/S,HIDEALL/S,HIDEOTHER/S,HIDEAPP/S,HIDEAPPOTHER/S,SHOW/S,SHOWALL/S,SHOWOTHER/S,SHOWAPP/S,SHOWAPPOTHER/S"@{par}

HIDE/S: The active window will be hidden.@{par}

HIDEALL/S: All windows will be hidden.@{par}

HIDEOTHER/S: All windows beside the active one will be hidden.@{par}

HIDEAPP/S: All windows of the same application will be hidden.@{par}

HIDEAPPOTHER/S: All windows which are not related to the tame application will be hidden.@{par}

SHOW/S: The active window will be visible again.@{par}

SHOWALL/S: All windows will be visible again.@{par}

SHOWOTHER/S: All windows beside the active will be visible again.@{par}

SHOWAPP/S: All windows that are owned by the same application will be visible.@{par}

SHOWAPPOTHER/S: All windows that are not owned by the same application will be visible.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowMaximise" "Macros - WindowMaximise"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowMaximise"}

Maximises the active window.

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowMinimise" "Macros - WindowMinimise"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowMinimise"}

Minimises the active window.

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowMove" "Macros - WindowMove"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowMove"}

By using this function it's possible to move the active window. Some arguments
are available to selection all options:@{par}

CENTER/S,LEFT/S,UP/S,RIGHT/S,DOWN/S,PLEFT/K/N,PUP/K/N,PRIGHT/K/N,PDOWN/K/N@{par}

CENTER/S does what it says. The direction switches just move the window to the
screen border. The P#? directions move the window by a specific number of
pixel.@{par}

Examples:@{par}

WindowMove Center PLeft 10@{par}

Centres the window and moves it 10 pixel to the left.@{par}

WindowMove Up Left PDown 20 PRight 10@{par}

This will move the window into the left top edge of the screen and 20 pixel down and 10 pixel to
the right.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowNext" "Macros - WindowNext"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowNext"}

This function forces the next window to be activated.@{par}

NOTOFRONT/S,ALLOWWB/S,HIDE/S@{par}

NOTOFRONT simply causes the window will be activated, but not pulled to front.

ALLOWWB allows to browse though workbench windows which are borderless and/or in
background, like standard workbench screen window.@{par}

HIDE: The current window will be hidden. @{b}MorphOS only@{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowPrev" "Macros - WindowPrev"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowPrev"}

This function forces the prev window to be activated.@{par}

NOTOFRONT/S,ALLOWWB/S,HIDE/S@{par}

NOTOFRONT simply causes the window will be activated, but not pulled to front.

ALLOWWB allows browsing to borderless and backdrop workbench windows like the
standard screen backdrop window.@{par}

HIDE: The current window will be hidden. @{b}MorphOS only@{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowToBack" "Macros - WindowToBack"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowToBack"}

The active window will be pushed to the back. It stays selected.

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowToFront" "Macros - WindowToFront"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowToFront"}

The active window will be moved to the front. It stays selected.

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowTopLeft" "Macros - WindowTopLeft"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowTopLeft"}

The active window will be moved into the top left edge of the screen.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowTopRight" "Macros - WindowTopRight"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowTopRight"}

The active window will be moved into the top right edge of the screen.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowZip" "Macros - WindowZip"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowZip"}

The active window will be maximised or minimised, depending on it's previous state.

@endnode
@node "MacrosReqOk" "Macros - ReqOk"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "ReqOk"}

By using this command you can confirm a requester. (LCOMMAND c).@{par}

This command requires no @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}!@{par}

Example:@{par}

ReqOk@{par}

Creates a "LCOMMAND c" input event.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosReqCancel" "Macros - ReqCancel"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "ReqCancel"}

By using this command you can abort a requester. (LCOMMAND v).@{par}

This command requires no @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}!@{par}

Example:@{par}

ReqCancel@{par}

Creates a "LCOMMAND v" input event.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosMouseClick" "Macros - MouseClick"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "MouseClick"}

This command allows to simulated mouse buttons. Several options are available:@{par}

MIDDLE/S,RIGHT/S,SINGLE/S@{par}

Without arguments MouseClick is performing a double click with the left mouse button. By adding
"MIDDLE" and "RIGHT" you can select other buttons. SINGLE turns the double click into a single
click.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosMouseMove" "Macros - MouseMove"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "MouseMove"}

This command allows to move the mouse pointer without touching the mouse. Just use the following
options:@{par}

LEFT/K/N,RIGHT/K/N,UP/K/N,DOWN/K/N@{par}

Without arguments the mouse pointer isn't moving. Please note that depending on the screen mode the
mouse steps may be reduced by the input system. This may cause that only each second pixel is moving
the pointer.@{par}

Examples:@{par}

MouseMove Left 10 Up 10@{par}

The mouse pointer is moving 10 pixel to the left and 10 pixel up.@{par}

MouseMove Right 10 Up 15@{par}

The mouse pointer is moving 10 pixel right and 15 pixel up.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosColdReboot" "Macros - ColdReboot"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "ColdReboot"}

This command will reboot your system and all reset resident data (viruses, RAD, OS3.x
ROM Updates) will be kicked out of memory.@{par}

After rebooting the system is in the same state as if you turned it off and on again!@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWarmReboot" "Macros - WarmReboot"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WarmReboot"}

This command restarts your system!

@endnode
@node "MacrosIEvent" "Macros - IEvent"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "IEvent"}

IEvent is the system name for "input event". By using this command you can
simulate input sequences. Let's say it easy: You can create one or more keys by
using this command.@{par}

This command requires some @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}:@{par}

CLASS/K/A,STREAM/K,STRING/K,CODE/K,QUALIFIER/K,-QUALIFIER/K,X/K,Y/K,
LSHIFT/S,RSHIFT/S,CAPSLOCK/S,CONTROL/S,LALT/S,RALT/S,LCOMMAND/S,RCOMMAND/S,
NUMERICPAD/S,REPEAT/S,INTERRUPT/S,MULTIBROADCAST/S,MIDBUTTON/S,RBUTTON/S,LEFTBUTTON/S,
-LSHIFT/S,-RSHIFT/S,-CAPSLOCK/S,-CONTROL/S,-LALT/S,-RALT/S,-LCOMMAND/S,-RCOMMAND/S,
-NUMERICPAD/S,-REPEAT/S,-INTERRUPT/S,-MULTIBROADCAST/S,-MIDBUTTON/S,-RBUTTON/S,-LEFTBUTTON/S

@{MS "CLASS"}

Describes the argument type. Currently only "RAWKEY" and "RAWMOUSE".

@{MS "STRING"}

STRING is only valid when using the keyboard class @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"}. "String hello" creates the keyboard
input "hello". @{b}Please note that the whole string will be translated into real key codes by the system.
This causes a delay before output.@{ub}

@{MS "STREAM"}

STREAM is only valid when using the keyboard class @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"}. The "text" must be specified as hex string.
STREAM "20" creates a small "a". Qualifier code are special, because they are processed immediately.
STREAM "6120" creates a "A", because 61 is the code for the left shift key. All following key codes
are processed with the shift key until you release shift by using "E1", which is the rawkey code for
releasing the left shift key.

@{MS "CODE"}

A single IEvent information. The specific values are depending on the used class. "69" represents the
right mouse button in the "RawMouse" class. Within the rawkey class only raw key codes are valid.

@{MS "QUALIFIER"}

This 16 bit value allows to set one or more specific qualifiers. When using the "String" mode this value
isn't effective.

@{MS "-QUALIFIER"}

Here it's possible to specify one or more specific qualifier to pass through. E.g. if the LSHIFT bit is
set, the current state of the left shift key is used.

@{MS "X and Y"}

These are the delta cords. When using the RAWMOUSE mode the mouse is moving by the number of pixel
specified here. To move the mouse left or up it's required to specify negativ values. (e.g. fffe)

@{MS "All the other switches"}

The other switches are working exact like the "Qualifier" or "-Qualifier" versions. This is more
user friendly than typing the hex values. You can use any combination of qualifier.

Examples:@{par}

IEvent Class @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"} String "Guido Mersmann"@{par}

creates the keyboard input "Guido Mersmann"@{par}

IEvent Class @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"} Stream "4c4c"@{par}

creates two "cursor up" keys.@{par}

IEvent Class @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"} Stream "612020E120"@{par}

This one is a little more komplex. "61" is the @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"} code for the left shift key. The next two values are "20".
These are creating two "a"s. Then an "E1" is following. It's the shift key again, but this time the release
version (61+80). The last "a" ("20") is small again. The output is "AAa". I know this isn't the easiest way to
create this output, but it's just an example.

IEvent Class @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"} Stream "4c4c" -lshift@{par}

this one creates two "cursor up". If the left shift key is pressed two "shift cursor up" will
be created"@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosEject" "Macros - Eject"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "Eject"}

By using this command you can control CD/DVD/ZIP/SCSI drives media and trays.@{par}

This command requires some @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}:@{par}

DEVICE/A,UNIT/N,LOCK/S,UNLOCK/S,EJECT/S,LOAD/S,TOGGLE/S,JIFFIES/N

DEVICE/A        : Always needed! Specify drive name like "cd0:" or device name like "scsi.device".@{par}
UNIT/N          : device unit. Only needed when using device name with the DEVICE option. Default is 0.@{par}
LOCK/S          : Tray or media will be locked and can't be removed/opened.@{par}
UNLOCK/S        : Tray or media gets unlocked and can be removed/opened again.@{par}
EJECT/S         : Ejects media or opens drive tray.@{par}
LOAD/S          : Media/tray gets sucked in.@{par}
TOGGLE/S        : Media/tray will change it's current state. (Default if no other command is selected).@{par}
JIFFIES/S       : If TOGGLE is failing for some reason try to change the default value of 10..@{par}

Examples:@{par}

Eject cd0:@{par}

Opens tray of cd drive if it's closed. If it's closed it will be opened.@{par}

Eject cd0: unlock toggle lock@{par}

Tray gets unlocked, then the tray state changes from open to close or vice
versa and finally the tray gets locked again. You can't open the tray by using the
drives eject button, because it stays locked.@{par}

Eject zip:@{par}

ZIP drives do not support media load, so this option allows to just eject it.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosCut" "Macros - Cut"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "Cut"}

By using this command you can create a clipboard cut event.@{par}

This command requires no @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}!@{par}

Example:@{par}

Cut@{par}

Creates a "RCOMMAND x" input event.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosCopy" "Macros - Copy"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "Copy"}

By using this command you can create a clipboard copy event.@{par}

This command requires no @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}!@{par}

Example:@{par}

Copy@{par}

Creates a "RCOMMAND c" input event.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosPaste" "Macros - Paste"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "Paste"}

By using this command you can create a clipboard paste event.@{par}

This command requires no @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}!@{par}

Example:@{par}

Paste@{par}

Creates a "RCOMMAND v" input event.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosIRComSend" "Macros - IRComSend"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "IRComSend"}

This command allows to send out ir signals to television sets, cd, dvd players
and anything else which is listening to ir codes. This feature requires the
@{b}IRCom@{ub} driver and compatible hardware.@{par}

Some @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"} are required for operation:@{par}

UNIT/K/N, KEYS/A/M@{par}

UNIT/K/N     : Specifies the IRCom hardware number. Default is 0L. Only required when you're@{par}
               using more than one ircom compatible hardware@{par}

KEYS/A/M     : Here you can define one or more keys in IRCom format to send out.@{par}

For more information on IRCom and it's usage contault the IRCom Manual.@{par}

Examples:@{par}

IRComSend play\@cdplayer@{par}

Sends the "play" signal to the cd player. Of course the remote "cdplayer" and
the key "play" must be available within the ircom database.@{par}

IRComSend +10\@cdplayer 1\@cdplayer 2\@cdplayer@{par}

Send the +10 signal followed by an "1" and a "2". The CD player is selecting
track 12.@{par}

@endnode

